WEBVTT

00:06.965 --> 00:08.216
WILL: <i>When I was a kid,</i>

00:08.633 --> 00:12.095
my grandmother used to say
all the best things in life

00:12.178 --> 00:14.055
lived on the other side of fear.

00:14.931 --> 00:16.516
I sure hope Gigi was right.

01:05.982 --> 01:07.776
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

01:08.610 --> 01:09.819
DIVA: Will, welcome aboard.

01:10.111 --> 01:13.031
-Diva! How are you? How are you?
-I'm good!

01:13.740 --> 01:15.033
You're just in time.

01:18.161 --> 01:21.498
-That is fantastic.
-Yeah, this is the<i> Nadir.</i>

01:21.623 --> 01:24.084
And she's gonna be our vessel
into the depths.

01:24.167 --> 01:25.627
-"The <i>Nadir"?</i>
<i>-Nadir.</i>

01:29.130 --> 01:30.173
What do you think?

01:30.673 --> 01:34.427
That's straight off a movie set.
That's science fiction.

01:36.596 --> 01:39.891
<i>We're going down to the bottom</i>
<i>of the ocean in this thing.</i>

01:43.812 --> 01:45.396
I'm gonna be honest, I'm a little nervous,

01:45.480 --> 01:47.023
'cause that submersible is just a...

01:47.148 --> 01:51.027
it's just a little... it's a little ass...
it's a little ass thing,

01:51.152 --> 01:52.654
and there's gonna be three people
in there.

01:53.863 --> 01:55.198
<i>This is tricky...</i>

01:55.615 --> 02:00.745
because in the real world,
I'm frightened of water.

02:05.500 --> 02:06.668
Watch your head.

02:06.793 --> 02:08.962
-You have another wall. Watch your head.
-Absolutely.

02:09.212 --> 02:10.797
<i>So, this is a biggie.</i>

02:11.714 --> 02:15.969
<i>Three thousand feet down</i>
<i>in a plastic bubble.</i>

02:16.052 --> 02:17.178
-MAN: Up the steps.
-Up the steps.

02:17.262 --> 02:19.055
Face the front of the sub, sit here.

02:19.222 --> 02:20.974
-Yeah.
-You're aimin' for the center console.

02:21.057 --> 02:23.143
It's near the lamp. And pop your feet in.

02:23.434 --> 02:26.729
Right here, Will. Slide on in. Yeah!

02:26.855 --> 02:29.023
-And then I'll get you to stand on there.
-WILL: Yeah.

02:29.107 --> 02:30.191
That's it.

02:30.275 --> 02:31.943
-And then you're gonna sit on that one.
-WILL: Ooh.

02:32.026 --> 02:33.236
-MAN: There you go.
-(GRUNTS)

02:33.403 --> 02:35.321
-MAN: Squeeze on in.
-(GRUNTS)

02:37.115 --> 02:39.117
-Wow.
-There's a water bottle.

02:39.200 --> 02:41.870
-The water bottle.
-And some more snacks.

02:41.953 --> 02:44.789
-I'll put your snacks down.
-This is, uh, snug.

02:45.665 --> 02:46.749
MAN: Diva's next.

02:47.500 --> 02:48.835
I'm coming.

02:53.173 --> 02:55.383
-So, she's like a gazelle.
-(MAN LAUGHING)

02:55.466 --> 02:58.845
WILL: Or should it be a sardine,
just squeezing into the can.

02:59.387 --> 03:01.181
-She knows what's she's doing.
-DIVA: Done this a bit.

03:02.724 --> 03:04.976
All right, I'm gonna give you
a quick safety brief.

03:05.727 --> 03:08.146
Both of you have a built-in
breathing system.

03:08.271 --> 03:10.523
If you need to,
it's just a standard scuba rig.

03:10.607 --> 03:12.609
-If I let... Yeah, if I tell you to...
-So, we go like that? Boom.

03:12.692 --> 03:14.277
...just pop it in your mouth,
then breathe normally.

03:14.360 --> 03:15.361
Okay. Mm-hmm.

03:15.486 --> 03:18.114
And if something happens to me,
there's a button under here.

03:18.198 --> 03:19.324
-Okay.
-All right?

03:19.407 --> 03:20.450
-Yellow.
-Yellow button.

03:20.533 --> 03:21.701
-The yellow button.
-Right there.

03:21.826 --> 03:23.578
-Press the tool, and...
-Oh, Jesus.

03:23.786 --> 03:27.457
-(LAUGHS)
-I've broken it already. Mayday, sorry.

03:27.916 --> 03:29.709
Press the tool, and let them know,

03:29.792 --> 03:31.336
-"X-ray, X-ray, X-ray."
-Okay.

03:31.920 --> 03:33.296
MAN: Okay, any questions?

03:33.880 --> 03:35.715
Have you ever crashed
one of these things into something?

03:35.798 --> 03:37.884
-Oh, yeah. All the time. Oh, yeah.
-All the time. Yeah, great.

03:42.096 --> 03:43.681
-Are you actually nervous?
-Huh?

03:43.932 --> 03:46.517
-DIVA: Are you actually nervous?
-Just a little bit. It'll be fine, though.

03:51.981 --> 03:53.358
(INDISTINCT CHATTER OVER RADIO)

03:53.483 --> 03:55.610
MAN: <i>Echo, </i>Nadir,
<i>we are ready for the water.</i>

03:55.777 --> 03:56.986
Ready for water.

04:01.866 --> 04:03.117
(INHALES DEEPLY)

04:06.746 --> 04:08.581
(SUBMERSIBLE ENGINE WHIRRING)

04:12.752 --> 04:15.797
See y'all later... I hope.

04:26.224 --> 04:27.475
Little bit of tingle.

04:37.151 --> 04:38.278
MAN: Here you go.

04:43.533 --> 04:45.660
TOBY: <i>Echo, bridge, you are clear</i>
<i>to launch. Clear to launch.</i>

04:45.910 --> 04:49.622
Roger, clear to launch. Break.
All positions are lifting now.

05:00.133 --> 05:01.426
<i>And lift off.</i>

05:01.509 --> 05:02.969
-Hey.
-Boom. Hey.

05:03.052 --> 05:04.137
DIVA: Here we go.

05:15.273 --> 05:16.983
WILL: I definitely just got nervous.

05:29.537 --> 05:31.789
(CHUCKLES) Whoa.

05:37.712 --> 05:39.630
MAN: If your feet get wet, please tell me.

05:39.797 --> 05:42.508
-That would be terrible! Man.
-(BOTH LAUGHING)

05:59.817 --> 06:01.611
And we are detached.

06:03.738 --> 06:07.700
Not emotionally.
Emotionally, I'm still very attached.

06:53.871 --> 06:59.502
TOBY: <i>Control, control, </i>Nadir.
<i>Vent secure, life support running. Over.</i>

07:00.128 --> 07:04.006
<i>Nadir,</i> control. Roger.
Surpassing five-zero meters. Descending.

07:13.683 --> 07:17.770
DIVA: <i>Some of my earliest memories</i>
<i>actually revolve around the ocean.</i>

07:19.522 --> 07:22.859
We'd be out on the boat,
and I would desperately,

07:22.942 --> 07:26.529
absolutely desperately want to know
what was down there.

07:28.614 --> 07:30.741
<i>But I'm not sure Will feels that way.</i>

07:37.373 --> 07:39.250
The circle of light above us is shrinking.

07:39.333 --> 07:40.543
MAN: Yeah, absolutely.

07:45.715 --> 07:50.094
WILL: <i>One thousand meters, 3,300 feet.</i>

07:50.928 --> 07:54.807
<i>A place so deep,</i>
<i>not even light gets down there.</i>

07:58.436 --> 08:02.106
<i>But what exists in total darkness?</i>

08:07.069 --> 08:08.237
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

08:08.488 --> 08:11.032
WILL:<i> Back on the surface,</i>
<i>other members of our team</i>

08:11.199 --> 08:13.117
<i>are asking the same question.</i>

08:24.337 --> 08:26.422
MELISSA:<i> There are a lot of people</i>
<i>who are afraid of the dark.</i>

08:29.467 --> 08:30.468
<i>And I'm one of them.</i>

08:38.518 --> 08:42.855
<i>I got bitten and dragged</i>
<i>by an American crocodile in the dark,</i>

08:42.939 --> 08:45.775
<i>and it's kinda made me a little bit wary.</i>

08:47.109 --> 08:51.030
WILL: <i>But not wary enough</i>
<i>to stop her canoeing at night</i>

08:51.113 --> 08:52.573
<i>in a glass-bottom boat.</i>

08:57.995 --> 09:00.623
MELISSA: <i>Part of being an explorer</i>
<i>is overcoming your fears,</i>

09:00.706 --> 09:02.500
<i>and when you do that...</i>

09:05.336 --> 09:07.380
<i>that's when you get to see the magic.</i>

09:10.967 --> 09:12.051
(SHRIEKS)

09:19.725 --> 09:20.977
We have life.

09:27.775 --> 09:30.361
<i>This water is full of tiny creatures.</i>

09:31.195 --> 09:33.906
<i>Disturb them,</i>
<i>and they burst into sudden light.</i>

09:35.950 --> 09:38.286
<i>You row through them,</i>
<i>and you create a light storm.</i>

09:49.922 --> 09:50.965
(LAUGHS)

09:52.216 --> 09:54.135
<i>We think it might be a defense.</i>

09:55.136 --> 09:58.014
<i>Like turning on a security light</i>
<i>to reveal intruders.</i>

09:59.807 --> 10:01.142
Oh, look at that.

10:02.018 --> 10:03.060
Wow.

10:05.438 --> 10:08.858
<i>Any movement in the water</i>
<i>picks up a glow, even these fish.</i>

10:17.783 --> 10:19.744
Here, sharky, sharky.

10:28.044 --> 10:29.920
Oh, yeah! That is a nurse shark.

10:30.338 --> 10:32.923
That's gorgeous. Look at his tailbeats.

10:37.178 --> 10:39.055
<i>This world is far from dark.</i>

10:40.848 --> 10:44.226
<i>Its constellations, its stars swirling</i>
<i>underneath your fingers</i>

10:44.310 --> 10:45.811
<i>and underneath your paddles.</i>

10:54.695 --> 10:58.032
<i>It's the most beautiful thing</i>
<i>I've ever seen.</i>

11:01.535 --> 11:04.330
<i>A magical world</i>
<i>that you'd never experience</i>

11:04.413 --> 11:06.374
<i>if you stuck to the safety of the day.</i>

11:11.337 --> 11:12.463
(GIGGLES)

11:20.471 --> 11:23.265
WILL: So, we're losing light
as we go down.

11:24.392 --> 11:26.727
And with that, the colors.

11:26.852 --> 11:30.272
DIVA: Exactly, so, white light
is made of lots of colors.

11:30.648 --> 11:33.859
And as it hits the water,
different colors

11:33.943 --> 11:35.611
get absorbed before others.

11:35.820 --> 11:37.113
ROYGBIV.

11:38.739 --> 11:42.159
That's how my grandmother
taught me the rainbow. ROYGBIV.

11:42.326 --> 11:44.787
-(LAUGHS)
-WILL: So, you know, red, orange, yellow,

11:44.954 --> 11:49.291
green, blue, indigo, violet.
Got it. So, red goes, orange goes,

11:49.375 --> 11:50.543
-yellow goes...
-Exactly.

11:50.668 --> 11:54.880
So, it's like blue is the last to go,
and that's why everything looks blue

11:55.005 --> 11:56.757
in the ocean. Check your shirt out.

11:57.717 --> 12:01.762
-Wow!
-(LAUGHS)

12:02.805 --> 12:05.391
That's crazy.

12:06.642 --> 12:11.480
We were picking wardrobe,
and they kept demanding the red shirt.

12:11.564 --> 12:13.858
-They kept demanding...
-What did you think it was for?

12:13.983 --> 12:16.110
I... I didn't know, I was like,
"I wanna be an explorer, man."

12:16.235 --> 12:17.820
(ALL LAUGH)

12:20.698 --> 12:22.825
DIVA: We're gonna just
be in a blue world soon.

12:24.118 --> 12:25.202
-And then, uh...
-Wow.

12:26.495 --> 12:27.496
And then...

12:28.247 --> 12:29.373
-A dark world.
-Dark world.

12:34.920 --> 12:38.758
<i>We've only just started,</i>
<i>and already the light from the surface</i>

12:38.841 --> 12:40.092
<i>is fading.</i>

12:40.634 --> 12:43.721
But before the dark, there's twilight.

12:44.263 --> 12:46.974
(INSECTS CHIRPING)

12:47.808 --> 12:51.479
WILL: <i>A world we think of as having</i>
<i>very little color.</i>

13:03.324 --> 13:08.204
CORY: <i>As night falls, the world</i>
<i>as we know it totally disappears.</i>

13:09.246 --> 13:10.998
<i>It disintegrates around you.</i>

13:15.044 --> 13:18.297
<i>Our eyes struggle to make out</i>
<i>our surroundings.</i>

13:19.507 --> 13:20.633
I can hear it.

13:21.675 --> 13:24.136
I can hear it getting louder. Yeah.

13:24.428 --> 13:26.347
<i>-Garuga...</i>
<i>-Garuga</i> is coming.

13:39.151 --> 13:41.278
(WATER RUSHING)

14:14.603 --> 14:18.357
CORY: <i>Sometimes, during a full moon,</i>
<i>when the skies are clear...</i>

14:19.358 --> 14:22.111
<i>a ghostly arc of light</i>
<i>appears in the mist.</i>

14:24.405 --> 14:25.823
<i>It's a moonbow.</i>

14:33.038 --> 14:37.585
<i>It's nearly impossible to see.</i>
<i>It's like this thin, grey line in the air</i>

14:37.751 --> 14:40.629
<i>that's stretching out</i>
<i>over the entire gorge.</i>

14:41.130 --> 14:44.300
<i>But with the right camera</i>
<i>and the right lens,</i>

14:44.550 --> 14:47.511
<i>you can see the line</i>
<i>for what it really is.</i>

14:50.681 --> 14:54.476
<i>It's a rainbow,</i>
<i>but it's created by the moonlight.</i>

14:56.937 --> 14:58.480
LIDIO: It's beautiful here, isn't it?

14:58.939 --> 15:00.107
CORY: This is perfect.

15:15.706 --> 15:19.251
<i>The white light is bouncing off</i>
<i>water droplets in the air,</i>

15:19.335 --> 15:21.253
<i>just like it does after a rainstorm.</i>

15:26.133 --> 15:30.304
<i>But here's the thing.</i>
<i>Moonlight isn't actually strong enough</i>

15:30.471 --> 15:33.015
<i>to activate our color vision.</i>

15:33.474 --> 15:37.102
<i>So, the moonbow remains hidden</i>
<i>in plain sight.</i>

15:38.312 --> 15:42.524
<i>It's a world of color that is just</i>
<i>completely hidden in darkness.</i>

15:49.114 --> 15:51.784
WILL: <i>The ocean has twilight, too.</i>

15:52.451 --> 15:54.370
Go down below 200 meters,

15:54.453 --> 15:57.122
and you're getting beyond the reach
of sunlight.

15:57.873 --> 16:02.461
And the twilight zone is full of things
no one has ever seen before.

16:07.549 --> 16:14.181
MAN: Control, control, <i>Nadir.</i>
Depth, 700 meters, descending. Over.

16:15.474 --> 16:17.935
-(SUBMERSIBLE CLUNKING)
-MAN: Did you hear that clunk then?

16:18.060 --> 16:19.770
-WILL: Yes, I did.
-MAN: That's the sphere telling us

16:19.895 --> 16:21.146
-we're getting deep.
-WILL: Yeah.

16:21.522 --> 16:22.856
(DIVA GASPS)

16:26.193 --> 16:28.362
-Okay, shall we do some exploring?
-WILL: All right.

16:29.279 --> 16:30.280
I guess.

16:37.454 --> 16:40.207
WILL: This feels just like <i>Star Wars.</i>

16:40.749 --> 16:42.710
I keep expecting to see the Death Star.

16:42.793 --> 16:44.086
-(DIVA LAUGHING)
-(MAN LAUGHING)

16:46.547 --> 16:49.967
-WILL: Do you ever get used to this?
-DIVA: Not really.

16:53.303 --> 16:55.931
Can you believe that more people
have been into space

16:56.015 --> 16:57.891
than the bottom of the ocean?

16:58.434 --> 17:03.272
I've only been down a handful of times
because these trips are just so rare.

17:05.232 --> 17:08.152
<i>Less than one percent of the deep ocean</i>
<i>has been explored.</i>

17:09.403 --> 17:12.364
<i>And even though</i>
<i>you're traveling deeper into the darkness,</i>

17:12.614 --> 17:14.491
<i>you actually start to see more.</i>

17:18.120 --> 17:19.163
Whoa.

17:19.997 --> 17:22.750
-DIVA: What?
-WILL: Wow.

17:24.084 --> 17:25.627
Well, that just came out of nowhere.

17:26.837 --> 17:29.423
That is a whole cliff.

17:36.013 --> 17:38.098
-That's amazing.
-DIVA: Isn't it?

17:40.392 --> 17:42.644
WILL: Maybe it is the Death Star.

17:46.356 --> 17:49.318
-DIVA: We have no idea how tall this is.
-Right.

17:49.401 --> 17:51.487
-DIVA: How far this goes, right?
-WILL: Yes, yes. Absolutely.

17:52.613 --> 17:55.657
DIVA: And before now,
no one has been here.

17:56.116 --> 17:57.117
WILL: Incredible.

18:05.375 --> 18:10.172
So, I could literally be one
of the first people to ever see this?

18:10.255 --> 18:11.256
DIVA: You could.

18:13.592 --> 18:16.595
WILL: Wait, aren't the explorer rules
that I get to name it?

18:16.678 --> 18:19.139
-DIVA: Yeah.
-WILL: The Fresh Peak.

18:19.306 --> 18:22.184
(ALL LAUGH)

18:25.896 --> 18:27.231
WILL: What is that?

18:28.273 --> 18:32.152
<i>Enypniastes, enypniastes, enypniastes.</i>
Go back, go back, go back.

18:34.696 --> 18:36.698
WILL: <i>It's weird as hell.</i>

18:39.660 --> 18:44.248
Okay, this is a type of sea cucumber.
Formal name, Enypniastes eximia.

18:44.373 --> 18:47.376
-But it has a bunch of nicknames.
-Mm-hmm.

18:47.543 --> 18:50.587
DIVA: My personal favorite
is the headless chicken monster.

18:50.712 --> 18:53.507
The headless chicken. Wow! Look at that.

18:56.260 --> 18:59.888
<i>It really does look</i>
<i>like a roast chicken...</i>

19:01.140 --> 19:05.352
<i>-that ate a giant Philly pretzel.</i>
-(DIVA LAUGHING)

19:09.648 --> 19:11.567
They're just one of my favorite things
to see.

19:12.234 --> 19:13.569
That is beautiful.

19:14.361 --> 19:18.615
You can see that it's red,
probably the most common color

19:18.740 --> 19:20.284
<i>of animals in the deep sea.</i>

19:20.659 --> 19:22.119
-WILL: <i>Wow!</i>
-DIVA:<i> Why do you think that is?</i>

19:22.619 --> 19:24.663
WILL: <i>That's a good question.</i>
<i>I don't know... Oh!</i>

19:24.997 --> 19:27.374
It would probably be for concealment,
right?

19:27.708 --> 19:29.960
-Yeah. They can hide. Yes, yes.
-Exactly!

19:30.335 --> 19:32.087
<i>-'Cause there's no red light.</i>
-WILL: <i>There's no red... They...</i>

19:32.254 --> 19:33.881
-DIVA: <i>You can't see them.</i>
-WILL: <i>You can't see 'em.</i>

19:33.964 --> 19:35.716
DIVA: <i>So, it's like they're wearing</i>
<i>an invisibility cloak.</i>

19:36.216 --> 19:40.137
WILL: <i>Oh, they act like my T-shirt, right?</i>
<i>That's my invisibility cloak.</i>

19:40.220 --> 19:41.305
DIVA: <i>Exactly.</i>

19:43.640 --> 19:46.560
Most of the creatures down here
can't even see red.

19:48.812 --> 19:51.982
WILL: <i>Yeah, I guess, they don't need to</i>
<i>in a blue world.</i>

19:55.944 --> 19:58.530
So, is everything down here red?

19:59.072 --> 20:01.450
-MAN: There's a jellyfish right here.
-Yeah?

20:01.533 --> 20:02.910
-Right in front of us.
-MAN: There.

20:02.993 --> 20:04.494
Whoo!

20:04.578 --> 20:06.872
DIVA: You'll see it's moving.
They'll all... Where the rainbow is.

20:06.955 --> 20:08.624
-Yes! Wow!
-DIVA: Yeah!

20:08.707 --> 20:09.708
(DIVA LAUGHING)

20:11.418 --> 20:13.337
That's amazing. Use your phone?

20:20.802 --> 20:24.306
<i>It's like a five-color light bulb</i>
<i>in the middle of it.</i>

20:27.226 --> 20:30.145
-DIVA: <i>That jelly actually has no color.</i>
-WILL: <i>What do you mean?</i>

20:30.229 --> 20:32.940
DIVA: <i>It only looks colorful</i>
<i>because we are shining a light on it.</i>

20:33.190 --> 20:34.691
WILL: <i>What do you... what's that mean?</i>

20:34.858 --> 20:38.528
That rainbow is never seen down here.

20:38.695 --> 20:41.740
-Because we have brought that white light.
-Right. Right. Right.

20:41.823 --> 20:45.077
DIVA:<i> And so, that is actually</i>
<i>not a real thing.</i>

20:45.369 --> 20:48.205
-Like, no animal down here sees that.
-WILL: Right. No animal sees it like that.

20:48.288 --> 20:49.498
Exactly.

21:01.927 --> 21:06.598
WILL: <i>Even though I can see this rainbow,</i>
<i>the creatures down here can't.</i>

21:08.850 --> 21:12.271
<i>And I can only see it because we brought</i>
<i>the right sort of light.</i>

21:15.440 --> 21:19.111
That approach can work
in all sorts of surprising ways.

21:19.361 --> 21:21.154
(INSECTS CHIRPING)

21:22.572 --> 21:25.158
WILL:<i> And it turns out,</i>
<i>you don't have to go that far</i>

21:25.242 --> 21:27.327
<i>to find hidden colors in the dark...</i>

21:28.328 --> 21:31.081
<i>just as long</i>
<i>as you have the right sort of light.</i>

21:53.520 --> 21:54.938
(BIRD SCREECHING IN DISTANCE)

21:55.731 --> 21:57.107
I heard something.

21:57.691 --> 21:58.942
They're right down here.

22:02.029 --> 22:03.864
I think they know we're here.

22:10.746 --> 22:12.831
-Why don't we go dark?
-GEORGE: Okay.

22:22.341 --> 22:23.925
Can you try the magic light?

22:27.596 --> 22:29.848
Oh, oh. Yeah,
there's movement right there.

22:31.808 --> 22:33.393
-That's it.
-(CHUCKLES)

22:33.560 --> 22:37.731
-It's like it's disco paint.
-It is. It's amazing, isn't it?

22:50.369 --> 22:52.996
GEORGE: Only a handful of people
in the world have ever seen this.

22:58.001 --> 23:01.338
JONATHAN: It's amazing,
how a little trick like this with UV light

23:01.505 --> 23:03.840
can just reveal a whole new world.
Who knew?

23:03.924 --> 23:06.301
GEORGE: (LAUGHING) Yeah.

23:06.385 --> 23:11.431
WILL: <i>And that's the thing. No one knew.</i>
<i>This is brand-new science.</i>

23:11.932 --> 23:16.061
<i>As we speak,</i>
<i>scientists are wandering randomly around</i>

23:16.144 --> 23:20.273
<i>with UV flashlights trying to see</i>
<i>what other animals</i>

23:20.357 --> 23:22.150
<i>might have this hidden power.</i>

23:23.318 --> 23:25.487
When you first saw this,
you must've thought you were, like,

23:25.570 --> 23:26.905
hallucinating or something.

23:28.198 --> 23:32.160
-My sanity was questioned, yes.
-GEORGE: (LAUGHING) Not the first time.

23:35.414 --> 23:38.792
WILL: <i>Who knew that animals</i>
<i>were putting on a secret light show</i>

23:39.042 --> 23:41.044
<i>-in our own backyards...</i>
-(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS)

23:42.254 --> 23:44.714
<i>...using colors that we can't see?</i>

23:45.507 --> 23:46.883
-(SQUIRRELS SQUEAKING)
-WILL:<i> Amazing.</i>

23:52.931 --> 23:56.601
<i>What we're looking for doesn't need</i>
<i>special lights.</i>

23:58.895 --> 24:02.899
<i>But what is left to see</i>
<i>when all light is gone?</i>

24:06.278 --> 24:09.322
DIVA: This is where we're probably
beginning to go into the midnight zone.

24:10.907 --> 24:12.117
No light.

24:14.661 --> 24:17.956
WILL: <i>To get to the midnight zone,</i>
<i>you need to go deep.</i>

24:18.999 --> 24:20.208
<i>Really deep.</i>

24:20.709 --> 24:23.628
<i>Close to the limits</i>
<i>of what this sub can handle.</i>

24:25.422 --> 24:27.549
(SUBMERSIBLE CLUNKING)

24:29.676 --> 24:31.553
(SUBMARINE CREAKING)

24:48.278 --> 24:50.280
DIVA: <i>So, as the sub is going deeper,</i>

24:50.614 --> 24:55.660
the most unnerving thing is the noises
it makes. This, like, horrible creaking.

24:56.161 --> 25:00.415
And that's the battle
between the sub and the ocean.

25:01.082 --> 25:05.337
And it's completely terrifying
if you stop for a second

25:05.462 --> 25:08.840
and think about the fact
that the only thing protecting you

25:09.090 --> 25:10.926
is about six inches of plastic.

25:16.014 --> 25:17.891
MAN: Toby, I'm gonna start
slowing down now.

25:18.808 --> 25:22.229
-TOBY: Nadir,<i> control, roger.</i>
-MAN: Here we go.

25:28.068 --> 25:30.570
WILL: Oh. We're at the bottom.

25:32.197 --> 25:34.199
MAN: That's about three inches
from the seabed.

25:35.992 --> 25:39.162
WILL: Coming in to land, Houston.
(IMITATING RADIO STATIC) Contact light.

25:39.287 --> 25:40.372
(DIVA LAUGHING)

25:40.497 --> 25:42.749
WILL: I always wanted to say that.
I just never really had a reason.

25:42.832 --> 25:44.125
(DIVA LAUGHING)

25:47.546 --> 25:50.173
I love this part,
when you see the seafloor

25:50.340 --> 25:52.717
just loom out of the depths at you.

25:55.845 --> 25:58.056
It's so surreal when you think about it.

25:58.181 --> 26:02.811
We're here,
a kilometer below the ocean surface.

26:11.570 --> 26:14.197
WILL: Personally, for you,
what is your life's goal,

26:14.322 --> 26:16.783
your hope for what you're doing?

26:17.826 --> 26:19.869
DIVA: 'Cause I'm from a developing
country...

26:20.036 --> 26:22.205
-WILL: Yeah.
-...we, as a nation,

26:22.289 --> 26:25.709
can't afford to explore
the majority of our area.

26:25.834 --> 26:27.752
-WILL: Wow, wow, wow, wow.
-Like, 90-something-percent

26:27.836 --> 26:29.838
of Trinidad's area is deep ocean.

26:29.963 --> 26:33.216
And we have no idea what's... what's there
because we don't have the expertise.

26:33.341 --> 26:34.467
I'm the only one.

26:35.427 --> 26:39.764
So, a big part of my work
is trying to change that.

26:40.974 --> 26:46.354
I've been on, like, 16 expeditions now,
and there is hardly ever anyone

26:46.438 --> 26:49.274
that looks like me, whether it's a woman,
a person of color,

26:49.357 --> 26:50.942
or a person from a developing country.

26:51.568 --> 26:53.528
-And I want that to change.
-WILL: Absolutely.

26:53.612 --> 26:56.197
DIVA: So, that's a big part of why I do
what I do.

26:56.281 --> 26:58.283
WILL: Got it. That's cool.

27:06.666 --> 27:11.463
Inside the sub at 3,300 feet.

27:12.380 --> 27:14.090
-We down here.
-(DIVA LAUGHING)

27:14.257 --> 27:16.509
We down here, y'all. We down here.

27:20.597 --> 27:23.350
Let's just say,
I got really, really inspired,

27:23.433 --> 27:24.643
and I just wanted to take a walk.

27:24.768 --> 27:27.562
-MAN: Probably last about half a second.
-(BOTH LAUGHING)

27:27.687 --> 27:29.856
-DIVA: And we would die in the process.
-WILL: Yeah.

27:29.939 --> 27:31.316
I probably won't do that then.

27:31.441 --> 27:32.901
-(DIVA LAUGHING)
-(MAN LAUGHING)

27:33.777 --> 27:35.695
DIVA: I always think,
"What a great way to go.

27:36.112 --> 27:37.238
"What a great story."

27:37.864 --> 27:39.991
WILL: A great story is one
that you get to tell.

27:40.116 --> 27:41.868
-Somebody else...
-MAN: Right, yeah.

27:41.951 --> 27:44.788
If somebody else has to tell it,
"Yeah, man, I was there that day,"

27:44.913 --> 27:46.581
it's like a less great story.

27:46.831 --> 27:48.333
(ALL LAUGHING)

27:55.590 --> 27:58.301
WILL: <i>If the pressure is that extreme,</i>

27:58.927 --> 28:02.430
you've gotta wonder, "What kinda creature
could live down here?"

28:04.099 --> 28:07.560
<i>Because even back on the surface,</i>
<i>explorers are finding</i>

28:07.644 --> 28:11.398
<i>some crazy, strange lifeforms</i>
<i>hiding in the dark.</i>

28:17.904 --> 28:21.741
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

28:28.164 --> 28:30.250
(WATER DRIPPING)

28:34.629 --> 28:37.549
ALEXANDER: <i>What is an astronaut</i>
<i>doing in a cave...</i>

28:41.344 --> 28:45.640
<i>300 meters below</i>
<i>the earth's surface in utter darkness?</i>

28:50.437 --> 28:56.151
<i>Going into a cave is very,</i>
<i>very similar to actually going to space.</i>

29:21.384 --> 29:25.597
<i>You lose colors,</i>
<i>and then you lose the concept of colors.</i>

29:29.434 --> 29:32.687
<i>If you look around,</i>
<i>most creatures that live down here</i>

29:32.771 --> 29:34.022
<i>are white or transparent.</i>

29:43.823 --> 29:45.825
<i>They have adapted to living in a cave,</i>

29:45.909 --> 29:48.995
<i>so they got rid of colors,</i>
<i>they got rid of eyes, even, totally.</i>

29:50.121 --> 29:52.081
<i>These creatures, they don't even see.</i>

30:01.633 --> 30:03.718
WILL: <i>An olm looks</i>
<i>like the kind of creature</i>

30:03.802 --> 30:05.762
<i>an astronaut might find.</i>

30:11.559 --> 30:14.312
<i>That weird, fleshy skin.</i>

30:16.898 --> 30:19.943
<i>They call olms the human fish.</i>

30:27.992 --> 30:32.664
<i>An alien that only needs to eat</i>
<i>every ten years.</i>

30:37.669 --> 30:39.546
<i>Which is just as well</i>

30:39.629 --> 30:42.257
<i>because they move too slowly</i>
<i>to catch much.</i>

30:46.052 --> 30:48.972
<i>A species that has been hidden away</i>
<i>in the dark</i>

30:49.055 --> 30:51.850
<i>for over 20 million years.</i>

30:53.268 --> 30:54.519
(GULPS)

31:06.155 --> 31:10.743
WILL: <i>If they found that thing in a cave</i>
<i>just a few hundred feet down,</i>

31:11.452 --> 31:15.748
<i>what the hell are we gonna find</i>
<i>at 3,000 feet below the sea?</i>

31:18.751 --> 31:21.045
-(SUBMERSIBLE ENGINE WHIRRING)
-(SUBMERSIBLE CLUNKING)

31:23.631 --> 31:29.178
MAN: Control. Control. <i>Nadir.</i>
Depth, 1,000 meters. Over.

31:35.685 --> 31:36.853
What was that?

31:38.563 --> 31:40.481
DIVA: There's only one way to find out.

31:41.608 --> 31:44.235
MAN: Yes. And there's a trick we play.

31:47.155 --> 31:49.365
(LIGHT SWITCHES FLICKING)

31:59.250 --> 32:00.251
WILL: Okay.

32:01.169 --> 32:03.338
Uh, what now?

32:04.339 --> 32:05.840
DIVA: Now, we'll see what's out there.

32:10.219 --> 32:15.433
MAN: So, shut your eyes.
Okay. One, two, three.

32:16.184 --> 32:17.226
(LIGHT SWITCH FLICKING)

32:19.437 --> 32:20.480
MAN: Eyes open.

32:22.815 --> 32:23.858
WILL: Like, nothin'.

32:24.400 --> 32:28.488
MAN: Try it again.
Let's turn on the flash. Okay, eyes shut.

32:31.240 --> 32:34.786
-One, two, three. Lights on.
-(LIGHT SWITCH FLICKING)

32:36.079 --> 32:38.665
MAN: Lights off. Eyes open.

32:41.960 --> 32:43.753
-DIVA: Wow! Wow!
-WILL: Woah!

32:43.878 --> 32:45.672
DIVA: Oh, my God! (LAUGHS)

32:45.755 --> 32:47.173
-WILL: Oh!
-DIVA: Wow!

32:48.341 --> 32:50.969
-WILL: Wow! Whoa!
-DIVA: Oh, my God. (LAUGHING)

32:51.469 --> 32:55.056
WILL: You have got to be kidding me.
Look at that.

32:55.390 --> 32:57.308
(MAN LAUGHING)

32:57.850 --> 33:01.854
WILL: It's like<i> Close Encounters.</i>
(HUMMING)

33:01.980 --> 33:04.107
-You know? (LAUGHS)
-(BOTH LAUGH)

33:07.235 --> 33:09.153
WILL: So, Diva, what is it?

33:09.362 --> 33:10.989
DIVA: Well, this is what we're here
to see.

33:11.197 --> 33:14.575
A hidden world you can only see
in total darkness.

33:14.701 --> 33:18.830
WILL: No, no, I know. But, like, act...
actually, scientifically, what is it?

33:19.497 --> 33:21.165
DIVA: It's bioluminescence, Will.

33:22.000 --> 33:26.004
It's a chemical reaction
using oxygen in the water to create light.

33:26.170 --> 33:27.463
But just look at it.

33:43.771 --> 33:46.190
WILL: <i>So, they're making their own light.</i>

33:46.441 --> 33:49.944
DIVA:<i> Exactly. And they use that light</i>
<i>to communicate.</i>

33:51.988 --> 33:55.033
-They are communicating with us, right?
-WILL: Mm-hmm.

33:55.825 --> 33:57.702
<i>-Like, "Mother! Mother!"</i>
-DIVA: <i>It's like </i>Avatar.<i> Yeah.</i>

33:57.827 --> 33:59.454
(ALL LAUGHING)

34:00.329 --> 34:02.665
WILL: Or, "Yo, man,
get them damn lights out my face."

34:02.749 --> 34:04.083
(ALL LAUGHING)

34:04.167 --> 34:05.835
DIVA: Or they're like,
"Do I wanna mate with you?"

34:05.918 --> 34:09.005
-I know, yeah. (LAUGHS)
-(BOTH LAUGH)

34:09.922 --> 34:14.927
WILL: There's like this whole language
I never even knew existed.

34:15.136 --> 34:18.181
Of all the space on the planet
in which animals can live...

34:19.265 --> 34:23.186
over 99 percent of it is in the oceans.

34:24.312 --> 34:28.608
And within that huge space,
nearly 80 percent of animals

34:28.691 --> 34:32.236
-use bioluminescence in some way.
-Wow!

34:32.695 --> 34:38.659
And so, actually, bioluminescence
may be one of the most common forms

34:38.743 --> 34:41.079
of communication on the planet.

34:41.913 --> 34:44.540
-WILL: That is mind-blowing.
-(DIVA LAUGHING)

34:46.292 --> 34:49.045
WILL: How did I not know
that this was in the world?

34:56.052 --> 34:57.386
MAN: Back to the surface.

34:58.262 --> 35:01.224
Control. Control. <i>Nadir.</i>

35:02.100 --> 35:05.561
Passing 400 meters, ascending. Over.

35:15.905 --> 35:17.782
Wow!

35:23.412 --> 35:25.623
-(DIVA CHEERS)
-WILL: That's crazy.

35:25.748 --> 35:27.125
(MAN LAUGHING)

35:28.626 --> 35:30.586
-WILL: Love that.
-(MAN LAUGHING)

35:32.088 --> 35:35.383
-This is right out of a romantic comedy.
-(BOTH LAUGH)

35:35.591 --> 35:40.012
I'm so putting this in a movie.
I am so putting this in a movie.

35:40.096 --> 35:42.723
MAN: I was just wondering
who you'd put in as me.

35:43.266 --> 35:44.767
-(WILL LAUGHING)
-(LAUGHS)

35:44.934 --> 35:47.228
-Oh, you'll be, like, Matt Damon.
-MAN: Oh, yeah. Matt Damon.

35:47.353 --> 35:48.938
-You know, somebody like that.
-MAN: Yeah.

35:49.021 --> 35:50.022
All right.

36:05.788 --> 36:07.039
MAN: Back to the sunshine.

36:09.584 --> 36:13.462
WILL: <i>We set out to find a hidden world</i>
<i>in the depths.</i>

36:16.549 --> 36:21.053
<i>And I discovered that there's more light</i>
<i>in the darkness than I ever imagined.</i>

36:22.221 --> 36:24.140
<i>From the deep, dark ocean...</i>

36:25.391 --> 36:28.060
<i>all the way to the sunlit surface...</i>

36:29.228 --> 36:32.231
<i>we live in a world of color.</i>

36:35.776 --> 36:36.944
MAN: Hold on!

36:37.320 --> 36:38.654
Yes, I like this part!

36:38.821 --> 36:42.200
-Yeah! (LAUGHING)
-(CHEERS)

36:43.034 --> 36:46.454
-DIVA: Will, you did it.
-Yay!

36:46.913 --> 36:47.914
Wow.

36:49.081 --> 36:52.335
-The sun just bursts back into your life.
-That was great.

36:52.460 --> 36:53.961
-WILL: Yeah! (LAUGHING)
-(LAUGHS)

36:54.128 --> 36:56.130
-That was definitely great.
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER OVER RADIO)

36:58.591 --> 37:00.468
WILL: <i>My grandmother used to say,</i>

37:00.635 --> 37:04.680
"God places the best things in life
on the other side of fear."

37:05.556 --> 37:10.937
Well, He also puts the brightest things
in life on the other side of darkness.

37:12.897 --> 37:17.235
<i>So much so,</i>
<i>that I only really began to see...</i>

37:18.277 --> 37:19.737
<i>when I descended...</i>

37:20.988 --> 37:22.198
<i>into the dark.</i>

37:27.662 --> 37:30.289
<i>Another hidden world awaits us.</i>

37:30.498 --> 37:32.416
<i>I fulfill a childhood dream,</i>

37:32.583 --> 37:36.379
<i>to witness one of the greatest</i>
<i>migrations on Earth,</i>

37:37.004 --> 37:40.258
<i>and discover that in the world of swarms,</i>

37:40.383 --> 37:44.220
<i>even unintelligent animals</i>
<i>can become super smart.</i>

37:44.929 --> 37:46.514
Wow!

37:49.308 --> 37:50.893
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

38:14.041 --> 38:16.043
(THEME MUSIC CONCLUDES)
